{
  "doc_id": "2020",
  "text": "Similar copy number variants (CNVs) have been found in many genes that are implicated in both ASD and schizophrenia [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Interestingly, different mutations in the same SHANK gene can result in schizophrenia phenotype instead of ASD-like phenotype [100••] . A nonsense mutation in SHANK3 that results in the replacement of an arginine (R1117X) with a stop codon has been identified in individuals who developed schizophrenia but had no developmental ASD or autistic features [CITATION_5] . A recent study has compared two mutant mouse lines: one line was created based on a mutation found in humans with ASD (InsG3680 mutation), and the other (R1117X mutation) was created based on the mutation that resulted in patient development of schizophrenia [CITATION_6] . Both lines exhibited postsynaptic signaling complex defects, social behavior deficits, and anxiety-like behavior. The R1117X mutant showed synaptic defects in the prefrontal cortex (PFC), while the InsG3680 mutants did not. It is still not fully clear how two different mutations in the same gene result in significantly reduced or no expression of SHANK3, yet exhibit different neurological phenotypes. The above study suggests that the different alleles of SHANK3 may result in alterations at different developmental stages or result in different levels of mRNA stability, resulting in varying neurobehavioral outcomes.",
